{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e890372-ab93-4d3c-b33e-d54c45c5d877","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the simplest option for .NET 8 and requires no install beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU profile\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need deeper OS-level detail:\n\nUse **PerfView** (free, from Microsoft):\n\n```powershell\n# Download & run (no install needed)\nPerfView.exe /nogui collect /ThreadTime /CircularMB:500 /MaxCollectSec:30\n```\n\nPerfView captures kernel-level CPU stacks (including native code, GC, JIT) — better for diagnosing thread contention or native interop issues.\n\n**TL;DR:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for simplicity. Escalate to PerfView if you need kernel/OS-level visibility.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38338f99-15e8-4003-9e86-3ed091fd9d71","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I should provide a concise, practical answer.\n\nThe best tool for this scenario is `dotnet-trace` or PerfView. For CPU profiling specifically on Windows, PerfView is the gold standard, but `dotnet-trace` is simpler and cross-platform.\n\nLet me give a concise recommendation.","outputTokens":418,"requestId":"D848:2A55B4:826312:9656D5:69FBEA3E"},"id":"72bc0066-f7eb-494f-a7bc-d6a7cf7f1d52","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:26:33.539Z","parentId":"a842eabd-46bd-461a-b6f5-b66edb213bda"}
